observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Management agreed to:

Fully implement all PPAs contained in the LDRRM Plan and Budget to achieve the envisioned purposes provided under the NDRRMC, DBM and DILG JMC No. 2013-1;

Monitor the implementation of the PPAs to attain full implementation of all LDRRM programs in compliance with the provisions of the aforementioned JMC;



Ensure that the LDRRM Office should be the exclusive project implementer of all the PPAs charged to the LDRRM Fund as required by Section 12 of RA No. 10121 and Item 7.0 of NDRRMC, DILG, DBM, and CSC JMC No. 2014-1 dated April 4, 2014;

Provide an appropriate storeroom solely for the use of LDRRM stockpiles to prevent contamination and unauthorized access; and


Monitor the stocks to avoid overstocking of food supplies that may result in spoilage of food and wastage.

We recommended the Management to:

Require the officials concerned to submit the GPB and GAD AR within the prescribed period to facilitate the timely evaluation and validation of the GAD PPAs;



Direct the GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) to observe proper planning, monitoring, and evaluation for GAD PPAs addressing gender issues and concerns to maximize its utilization, and for possible reallocation of funding for further GAD PPAs;

Prepare and submit the GAD Evaluation Report as required under         Item 5.7 of PCW, DILG, DBM, and NEDA JMC No. 2013-01; and

Direct the CAO and CSWD to reconcile the records and to make necessary adjustments, if warranted.

Instruct the Inventory Committee to continue the physical count of all PPEs, and reconcile the discrepancies provided in Chapter V of the handbook and Section 491 of the GAAM, Volume I;

Submit the necessary documentation enumerated in Items 7 and 8 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 for our evaluation, to address and rectify the deficiencies/lapses noted in the accounting of its PPE account and to ensure the fairness of its presentation in the statement of financial position; 

Submit the necessary documents related to the fire incident on June 06, 1998, for our evaluation in addressing the beginning balances; and

Avail of the remedies on one-time cleansing pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006

Revised the list of documentary requirements to be submitted by the newly hired and renewed COS personnel, to include the accomplishment of BIR Form 0605 as prescribed by RMC No. 51-2018;



Recompute the tax due to COS personnel, ensuring the exclusion of tardiness and other deductions to come up with taxable income as a basis in computing the tax withheld; 

Make inquiries and ask assistance from BIR for full compliance with tax requirements; and




Strictly comply with the provisions of RMC No. 51-2018.




Also, we encouraged the Management issue to a Memorandum Order for all employees for the strict observance of eight hours of work a day by implementing the break-in/break-out during lunch.

Direct the PhilHealth Section to strictly adhere to the guidelines, rules, and regulations prescribed by relevant PhilHealth Circulars concerning the processing of claims to be submitted to PhilHealth and carefully scrutinize all documents required to support claims for completeness and correctness and cause the filing thereof within the prescribed period to ensure reimbursement and avoid RTH and/or denial of claims;

Validate the causes of denied and RTH claims, and, explore all possible remedies to have them reconsidered by PhilHealth and monitor the deadlines set by PhilHealth for filing of claims and appeals to ensure collection thereof;




Employ additional personnel and cause the training of concerned PhilHealth Section personnel whenever there are changes in their assignments and updates in the policies, rules, and regulations on processing PhilHealth claims; and




Enable the system to generate relevant data for all types of claims from PhilHealth to ease monitoring and reconciliation with accounting records.

Direct the GAD Focal Point System to observe proper planning, monitoring, and evaluation for GAD programs addressing gender issues and concerns to maximize its utilization; and for possible reallocation, or reversion of funds for other GAD programs;

Prepare the GAD Evaluation Report within the prescribed period as required under Item 5.7 of PCW, DILG, DBM, and NEDA JMC No. 2013-01; 




Instruct the City Accounting Office and City Social Welfare and Development Office to reconcile the records, and to make necessary adjustments, if warranted; and

Strictly, comply with the provisions of the aforementioned JMC.

Ensure the timely recording of transactions and the corresponding tax withheld in compliance with IPSAS;




Coordinate with the City Treasurer’s Office for the timely submission of paid payrolls and disbursement vouchers for the former to record the transactions in the subsidiary ledger in the period it relates;

Ensure that corresponding taxes were recognized in the accounting records before remittance to BIR to avoid the abnormal balance in the subsidiary ledgers;




Reconcile the records of the subsidiary ledgers and the monitoring of remittances to identify errors to effect adjustments, if warranted; and

Make sure to withhold taxes for the accrued expenses supported by payrolls and other documents to prove the legality of claims.

We recommended the Management to:
Require the officials concerned to submit the GPB and GAD AR within the prescribed period to facilitate the timely evaluation and validation of the GAD PPAs;
Direct the GAD Focal Point System to observe proper planning, monitoring, and evaluation for GAD PPAs addressing gender issues and concerns to maximize its utilization, and for possible reallocation of funding for further GAD PPAs;
Prepare and submit the GAD Evaluation Report as required under         Item 5.7 of PCW, DILG, DBM, and NEDA JMC No. 2013-01; and
Direct the CAO and CSWD to reconcile the records and to make necessary adjustments, if warranted.

City Accounting Office (CAO) to prepare JEV for stale checks amounting to P28,359.55 and thereafter, furnish the City Auditor’s Office the copies of JEV for verification;

City Treasurer’s Office (CTO) to

Prepare check in replacement for check no.222989 amounting to P28,359.55 upon submission of the spoiled or stale check by the payee, and request for the certified copy of the DV from the Auditor for presentation to the Administrator/Local Chief Executive who shall countersign the check;


Send a written notice to the payees one month before the check becomes stale as required in Section 59 of the NGAS Manual;

Stale checks shall be reported and attached to the RCI prepared at the period of cancellation;

Prepare and submit the schedule of unreleased checks at year-end to the CAO for the preparation of the JEV to restore the cash equivalent of the unreleased checks; and

CTO and the CAO to monitor checks that are still not released at year-end so that appropriate adjustments should be made promptly.

Plan the conduct of physical count of inventories semestral to comply with the deadline on the submission of RPCI every July 31 and January 31;

Direct the CAO and GSO to complete the physical count and reconciliation of accounts before submission the CAO to make the necessary adjustments, if warranted, and for GSO to submit the necessary documents;

Instruct the Supply Officers to submit the SSMI regularly to the General Service Office and City Accounting Office to properly recognize the expense portion; and

Make sure that all supplies and materials in every Office are included in the physical count conducted by the General Service Office.

We recommended Management to:
Reconcile the variance between the books of accounts and the RPCPPE totaling P229,037,247.81 pursuant to Chapter V of the Handbook on Supply and Property Management System;
Maintain Property Cards pursuant to Section 119 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I;
Record the cost of improvements and derecognize the cost of demolished/replaced portion of properties in the books of accounts pursuant to Paragraphs 24 and 85 of IPSAS 17;
Prepare adjusting entries on the recorded semi-expendable properties, pursuant to Item 5.4 of the COA Circular 
No. 2016-006 dated December 29, 2016; and
Avail of the remedies provided under COA Circular 
No. 2020-006 for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, subject to the full compliance of the requirements of Item Nos. 7 and 8 thereof, to address and rectify the deficiencies/lapses noted in the accounting of its PPE account and to ensure the fairness of its presentation in the statement of financial position.

We recommended the City Health Office to:
Immediately inform the CAO and the GSO of all received donations, and submit the necessary supporting documents such as Delivery Receipts, Sales Invoice, Inspection and Acceptance Report (AIR) and Property Transfer Records (PTR), if any, for proper monitoring and recording purposes;
Prepare Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) on every requisition of supplies and materials issued and submit the same to the GSO for the preparation of SSMI;
We also recommended the Management to:
Require the City Accounting Office to prepare the necessary adjusting entries upon receipt of documents from the CHO and GSO to correct the balances of the affected inventory accounts.  Likewise, implement the use of perpetual inventory method in all regular purchases of supplies and materials;
Conduct physical count of inventories every semester, prepare complete reconciliation of accounts between RPCI and the books of accounts, and make the necessary adjustments, if warranted;
Instruct Supply Officers to consolidate weekly the RIS using the SSMI on regular basis and forward the report to the City Accounting Office to properly recognize the expense portion for the issued inventory accounts; and
Henceforth, strictly comply with Sections 114, 121 and 124 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I.

We recommended the Management to:
Reconcile the variance between the records of the CAO with the hospitals (NCH and CHO) for receivables from PhilHealth and prepare adjusting entries in the books for the variance and to correct the misclassified amount by debiting Due from GOCCs- PhilHealth and crediting Due from NGAs by P38,136,181.50;
Avail of the remedies provided in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016 on the Guidelines and Procedures on the Write-off of Dormant Receivable Accounts subject to the full compliance of the requirements of Section 7.0 and 8.0 thereof;
Reconcile the records of the CAO and GSO to reflect the correct amount of undelivered office and other supplies to the City;
Reclassify the abnormal balance of the receivable accounts to payable accounts to recognize the liability for overcollection;
Collect the amount of P169,754.54 which was erroneously paid twice against the service provider or deduct the same from the amount due to the supplier and/or to the person’s concerned liable for the double/erroneous payment; and
Provide explanation on the abnormal balance of the Other Receivable accounts, especially those arising from the utility expenses.

We recommended that the Management:
Direct the BAC Secretariat to consolidate meticulously and judiciously the PPMPs from various units, to be integrated into a workable APP, including the submission of APP-CSE for the common-use supplies and equipment as prescribed in GPPB Circular 08-2015 and GPPB Resolution No. 20-2015;
Make use of the APP in the determination of the proper mode of procurement that will be advantageous to the City and to avoid purchasing supplies/materials/equipment on a per department/office/ end-user unit basis;
Ensure that the PPMP and the consolidated APP shall be, at all times, consistent with the Appropriation Ordinances of the City for the year; and
Require the concerned department/office to regularly update their PPMPs and the BAC to accordingly update the APP once every six months to reflect the necessary revision for the approval of the Local Chief Executive (LCE).

We recommended the concerned offices to:
Assign a dedicated personnel to prepare the Monthly and Quarterly Report on Fund Utilization and Status of Program/Project Implementation and submit the same to the PIO and ICTO to facilitate posting thereof in the designated bulletin and website of the City pursuant to the requirements of the DBM LBC Nos. 125 and 128;
Henceforth, comply with the requirements of DBM LBC Nos. 125 and 128 on the reporting and posting requirements.

We recommended that Management:
Plan and execute timely the implementation of the PPAs to enumerate maximum use of the allotted budget for NCCPC Fund for the realization of the objectives of the PPAs and the benefits that will redound to its intended beneficiaries;
Henceforth, comply with the provisions of Section 15 of RA No. 9344, and Section 2 of DILG Memorandum Circular No. 2012-120 to ensure the protection of the rights and welfare of children.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that:

The CAO –

Confirm the investments/guaranty deposits with the Investee/Company concerned and complete the details in the SL, and thereafter, adjust/correct those that were already derecognized or applied in previous payments;
Update the Guaranty Deposit- Bill Deposit with the concerned agencies to come up with the more reliable amount of investment as of year-end; 

Secure copies of the certificates on investments recorded in the books from the available sources and current practice on investment in stocks and henceforth, to retain copies or proofs of ownership at all times as part of the City’s permanent file; and

The CTO secure at all times, all Investment certificates, like time deposits, treasury bills and stock certificates, which shall be inventoried showing their serial numbers, amounts and type of investments for the purpose of   turn over or transfer of accountability per Sections 116 and 117 of the Local Treasury Operations Manual.

We recommended that the:

City Accounting Office -

Adjust the Report of Fund Utilization for GAD by excluding in the column of “amount utilized” the goods procured which have not yet been delivered and are not yet due and demandable as of December 31, 2020 with a total amount of P0.294 million;

Reconcile the discrepancies of the allocation of GAD between the GPB and the CAO’s Report of Fund Utilization for GAD; 

Henceforth, reconcile the variances in the cost of expenditures of each PPA between the GAD Accomplishment Report and Fund Utilization Report as of the year-end, prior to submission of these reports to the COA and DILG-NCR;

GFPS-TWG -

Exclude the amount of P14.189 million representing the cost of drugs & medicines and   medical, dental & laboratory supplies which have not yet been delivered as of December 31, 2020, but were included in 2020 GAD Accomplishment Report as actual cost of expenditures attributed to GAD Budget;

Review the City’s enacted annual budget for Drugs &Medicines and Medical, Dental & Laboratory Supplies for a correct data/statistics reference in the application of attributing the programs budgets to the GAD;




Adjust/Include the budget of the Bayanihan Grant to the revised GPB, as an attributable cost in the GAD AR and effect any adjustments/changes accordingly to the GAD AR; and

Henceforth, prepare the GAD AR at the end of the year based on the enacted LGU budget and revised GPB to reflect a more realistic gender mainstreaming in the GAD AR, as provided under Section C.8 of JMC 2013-01 as amended by JMC 2016-1.

We recommended that the CTO and the CAD: 

Remit the monthly premium contributions to the GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth as well as the loan amortization payments to the said agencies intact and on time for the employees to continuously enjoy and maximize the benefits given by the same agencies to their qualified members and to avoid payment of penalties;

Adjust/correct the discrepancy of P375,319.04 on the ending balance between the financial statement and the subsidiary ledger of Due to GSIS, GF - Proper and Special Education Fund;

Investigate the nature and/or existence of unremitted contributions to PhilHealth amounting to P3.0 million, on the average, which remained outstanding for some time and carried forward as beginning balance in the books of accounts.

We recommended that the SWMB:
Adopt measures to promote and ensure the viability and effective implementation of RA No. 9003 by establishing MRFs in every Barangay, or clusters of Barangays;
Establish a centralized MRF as provided in the City’s Ten-Year Plan;
Provide the necessary support to component barangays either financially, technically or in any other manner deemed necessary in order to achieve the waste diversion goal of RA No. 9003; and
Revisit the City’s Ten-Year SWM Plan for proper updates or modifications upon proper consultations with the various sectors of the community to ensure its sustainability, relevance and effectiveness, and submit to the National SWM Commission for concurrence and approval.

We recomended that the CTO and the CAD:
Remit the monthly premium contributions to the GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth as well as the loan amortization payments to the said agencies intact and on time for the employees to continuously enjoy and maximize the benefits given by the same agencies to their qualified members and to avoid payment of penalties;
Adjust/correct the discrepancy of P375,319.04 on the ending balance between the financial statement and the subsidiary ledger of Due to GSIS, GF - Proper and Special Education Fund;
Adjust/correct the discrepancy of P3,127.81 on the ending balance between the financial statement and the subsidiary ledger of Due to Pag-IBIG GF - Proper in the amount of P(3,127.80); and
Investigate the nature and/or existence of unremitted contributions to PhilHealth amounting to P3.0 million, on the average, which remained outstanding for some time and  carried forward as beginning balance in the books of accounts.

We recommended for - 

The City Accountant to:

Sort the PPE according to its nature and add to the specific property the cost of the PPE when it is capitalizable and deduct the cost for the portion of the properties which were already demolished due to renovations/ improvements;




Exert extra effort to determine the details of property items without description/breakdown and lumped as beginning balances; 




Record the property properly according to its classification, specification and to the nature of PPE in accordance with the Revised Chart of Accounts for LGUs;




Update the Property/ Equipment Ledger Cards starting with the current year’s acquisition and recent years’ acquisitions until all PPE items are covered to monitor the additions, deductions and any adjustments relative to the PPE;

The City General Services Officer to –

Create an inventory committee team composed of members from different offices that will undertake a thorough actual physical count of the City’s PPE and record in the RPCPPE all PPEs actually found and counted;




Reconcile the RPCPPE with the CAO’s books of accounts and settle all variances including the undetermined “Beginning Balances” that were recorded in lumped amount without any details or description; and

Update Property/ Equipment Cards, starting with the current year’s acquisition and then recent years’ acquisitions until all PPE items are covered.

We recommended that the Management instruct the City Treasurer’s Office and City Assessor’s Office to:

Account for all the discrepancies noted between the CLT and AR for the taxable properties;



Account for the variance noted on tax exempt properties between the report submitted by the City Assessor and the AR; 



Require the owners whose real properties are exempted from taxes to submit sufficient supporting documents to prove such exemption, otherwise, these properties shall be listed as taxable; and

Re-assess the buildings and improvements of the property whose market values are P175,000.00 and below, which were previously exempted from the RPT and impose the corresponding tax level and tax rate for RPT and SET; and

Undertake a general revision of assessment and property classification as provided in Sections 219 and 220 of the LGC.

The City Accountant to -
Sort the PPE according to its nature and add to the specific property the cost of the PPE when it is capitalizable and deduct the cost for the portion of the properties which were already demolished due to renovations/improvements;
Exert extra effort to determine the details of property items without description/breakdown and lumped as beginning balances;
Record the property properly according to its classification, specification and to the nature of PPE in accordance with the Revised Chart of Accounts for LGUs;
Update the Property/Equipment Ledger Cards starting with the current year’s acquisition and recent years’ acquisitions until all PPE items are covered to monitor the additions, deductions and any adjustments relative to the PPE;
The City General Services Officer to -
Create an inventory committee team composed of members from different offices that will undertake a thorough actual physical count of the City’s PPE and record in the RPCPPE all PPEs actually found and counted;
Reconcile the RPCPPE with the CAD’s books of accounts and settle all variances including the undetermined “Beginning Balances” that were recorded in lumped amount without any details or description; and
Update Property/Equipment Cards, starting with the current year’s acquisition and then recent years’ acquisitions until all PPE items are covered.

We recommended that the Management instruct the City Treasurer’s Office and  City Assesssor’s Office to:
Account for all the discrepancies noted between the CLT and AR for the taxable properties;
Account for the variance noted on tax exempt properties between the report submitted by the City Assessor and  the AR;
Require the owners whose real properties are exempted from taxes to submit sufficient supporting documents to prove such exemption, otherwise, these properties shall be listed as taxable; and
Re-assess the buildings and improvements of the property whose market values are P175,000.00 and below, which were previously exempted from the RPT and impose the corresponding tax level and tax rate for RPT and SET for those properties whose market values exceeded  P175,000.00.

The City Engineer’s Office require the conduct of quality and material tests by DPWH accredited laboratories and submission of results before the payment of contractor’s billings;

The BAC include in the Special Conditions of the contract the conduct of the required minimum tests; and

The City Engineer assign/designate personnel who will supervise/conduct the tests.

Secure all the Memorandum of Agreements (MOAs)/ Contracts, disbursement reports and other relevant documents pertaining to the dormant accounts and cause the thorough verification of the nature or purposes of these funds to determine the status of the projects whether already completed, discontinued or abandoned;

Make the necessary adjustments in the books to determine unutilized balances and cause remittance to the Source Agency; and

On projects with remaining balances in the books, coordinate with the source agencies to reconcile the book balances with their records, and cause the preparation of the necessary correcting entries to arrive at the accurate balances of the Due to Other NGAs.

We recommended that Management direct:
The General Services Office (i) to provide an insurance of all its insurable properties to the GSIS to mitigate possible losses on the part of the City; and (ii) to submit an inventory list of insurable properties;
The Budget Office to allocate an adequate budget for insurance expense for the year.

The City Engineer’s Office require the conduct of quality and material tests by DPWH accredited laboratories and submission of  results before the payment of contractor’s billings;
The BAC include in the Special Conditions of the contract the conduct of the required minimum tests ; and
The City Engineer assign/designate personnel who will supervise/conduct the tests.

The BAC  follow the guidelines set by the GPPB in the use of ordering agreement;
The City Planning and Development Office  carefully plan all procurements to be included in  the Annual Procurement Plan as well as  the mode of procurement to be used;
The City Accountant require the supplier to post warranty security  before payment of claim;
The BAC prepare the NTP to determine if the supplier implemented the contract in the exact schedule within the stipulated time;
The BAC Chairman to include the end user as member of the bid and awards committee; and
The BAC to adhere with the rules and regulation of RA 9184 and its IRR, GPPB issuances such as circular guidelines, and resolutions in the conduct of procurement.

We recommended that - 

The City Health Office 
assume responsibility on the proper control of drugs/medicines and medical supplies received from different sources: a separate Acceptance Report with appropriate label be prepared for items received from the DOH; properly organize medicines and medical/dental supplies procured by General Services, DOH, and from different barangays and maintain them in a place with proper ventilation; maintain separate logbooks for receipts and issuances for proper accounting;

Prepare and render monthly to the City Accountant, the Summary of Drugs/Medicines and Medical/Dental Supplies and Material Issued supported by approved Requisition and Issue Slip for proper recording of expenses in the books of utilized medicines and medical/dental supplies coming from all sources;





Conduct periodic physical count of inventory and prepare the report using the Report on the Physical Count to the Inventory of Drugs/Medicines, Medical/Dental Supplies, etc. and submit to the City General Services for consolidation copy furnished the City Accountant for reconciliation. Separate RPCI shall be submitted for Inventories from other sources;

Reconcile/account the medicines worth P1,179,181.38 not received from DOH and P2,283,072.63 from other sources; and

The City Accountant take-up the donated inventories in the books in accordance with the IPSAS 12 and 23.

We recommended and the GAD focal person already noted the following:

establishment/strengthening of the GAD Focal Point System;

setting up/maintenance of GAD Database pursuant to PCW/DILG/DBM/NEDA JC No. 2013-1;


Align the GAD programs with its objectives.
